The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                                                                       7                                                                                                        
	 Calcutta: India captain Bhaichung Bhutia criticised big clubs like Mohun Bagan and East Bengals attitude to change coaches without giving them enough time to settle down. Any coach is good, provided you give him time and freedom. But the problem with our Calcutta clubs, Mohun Bagan and East Bengal, is that they dont give the coaches time and freedom to settle down, he said reacting to the appointment of Manuel Gomes as East Bengal coach.         
	 Calcutta: The executive committee of Mohun Bagan has unanimously decided to confer Mohun Bagan Ratna posthumously to the 10 players of the historic 1911 IFA Shield winning squad. Late Shibdas Bhaduri has already been conferred the honour.         
	 Madrid: Sandro Rosell will be the 39th president of Barcelona after winning a landslide vote among club members on Sunday, the Spanish champions said on their website . The 46-year-old businessman will replace Joan Laporta, who steps down this month.         
	 Zurich: Romania striker Adrian Mutu has been ordered to pay former club $20.7 million in damages by the Swiss Federal Supreme Court, six years after he was sacked for testing postive for cocaine.             
	 Madrid: Real Sociedad returned to La Liga after a three-year absence on Sunday, with a 2-0 victory over Celta Vigo sealing their position as second-division champions.           
	 Montreal: Germanys Michael Schumacher escaped a penalty after colliding with former teammate Felipe Massa during an eventful Canadian Grand Prix on Sunday.         
	 Estoril: Gaganjeet Bhullar carded a steady two-under 70 in the final round to sign off tied 30th at Portugal Open.        
	 Calcutta: Varun Julasaria and Ritika Kundu won the sub-junior boys and girls events at the CLT Table Tennis Championship on Monday.         
	Karachi: The PCB chairman Ijaz Butt has revealed that an appeals judge lifted bans and reduced fines on players penalised for indiscipline on his request.                                                                                                                                                           
